2.1.3 1PL

In Rasch model, \(a\) term is always fixed to 1, in 1PL model, \(a\) is free to vary, but the value is the same for all items. In the fitted 1PL model, \(a = 0.26\) for all items.

None of the items is the most informative, as the item information is just the first derivative of the item characteristic curve, which depends on \(a\) parameter (and which value is the same of all items in both Rasch and 1PL models).

2.1.4 2PL

V5, V15, V20, V29, V32, V34, V37, V41, V51

The negative discrimination is caused by ânegative wordingâ of those items.

The most informative item is V51.

\(r_{factor-total\ scores} = 0.536\), as opposed to Rasch model, for which \(r_{factor-total\ scores} = 1\)

2.2.1

data <- read_csv("epi_escore.csv")

reverse.items <- function(data, which.items) {
  rev.data <- sapply(data, function(x)
    as.numeric(x == 0))
  new.data <- data
  new.data[, which.items] <- rev.data[, which.items]
  return(new.data)
}

which.items <- paste0("V", c(5, 15, 20, 29, 32, 34, 37, 41, 51))

revdata <- reverse.items(data = data, which.items = which.items)

a_diff <- sum(abs(coef_tbl$original_a) - abs(coef_tbl$reversed_a))
b_diff <- sum(abs(coef_tbl$original_b) - abs(coef_tbl$reversed_b))

Parameters of ânegative-wordedâ items in model based on original data are additive inverse of parameters of model based on rescored data. Thus, sum of differences in absolute values of parameters \(\mathit{diff_a} = 0.0011466\); for \(b\) parameters, \(\mathit{diff_b} = 7.1219128\times 10^{-4}\). Ideally, those values should be zero. This does not apply probably due to some âfitting artefactsâ.

4

It may be convenient to introduce so-called âjitterâ in ShinyItemAnalysis plots.

Excerpt from ggplot2 documentation:

It adds a small amount of random variation to the location of each point, and is a useful way of handling overplotting caused by discreteness in smaller datasets.

Example here ;-)

without_jitter <- tibble(theta = fscores(fit2PL.mirt.rev),
       total_score = rowSums(revdata)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(total_score, theta)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(title = 'Without "jitter"')

with_jitter <- tibble(theta = fscores(fit2PL.mirt.rev),
       total_score = rowSums(revdata)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(total_score, theta)) +
  geom_point(position = "jitter") + # NOTE
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  labs(title = 'With "jitter"')

grid.arrange(without_jitter, with_jitter, ncol = 2)
